{{DISPLAYTITLE:{{mp|2010 AL|30}}}} {{Infobox planet | minorplanet=yes | background=#FFC2E0 | name={{mp|2010 AL|30}} | image= 2010al30-18frame-Goldstone.png | image_size = 265 | caption=[[Goldstone Deep Space Communications Complex|Goldstone]] [[radar astronomy|radar]] collage of asteroid {{mp|2010 AL|30}} | discoverer= | discovered=January 10, 2010 | alt_names=''none'' | mp_category=[[List of Apollo asteroids|Apollo]] [[Near-Earth object|NEO]]<ref name="jpldata"/> | epoch=13 January 2016 ([[Julian day|JD]] 2457400.5) | semimajor={{Convert|1.0466|AU|Gm|abbr=on}} | perihelion={{Convert|0.72437|AU|Gm|abbr=on}} | aphelion={{Convert|1.3688|AU|Gm|abbr=on|lk=on}} | eccentricity=0.30787 | period=1.07 [[Julian year (astronomy)|yr]] (391.07 [[Julian year (astronomy)|d]]) | inclination=3.8300° | asc_node=112.376° | arg_peri=97.711° | mean_anomaly=156.409[[Degree (angle)|°]] | avg_speed=28.5 | dimensions=~30 meters (elongated)<ref name="echo"/> | mass= | rotation={{Convert|0.14660|h|d|abbr=on|lk=on}} | spectral_type=? | abs_magnitude=27.2 | albedo= | single_temperature= | mean_motion={{Deg2DMS|0.92054|sup=ms}} /day | orbit_ref=<ref name=jpldata/> | uncertainty=2 | moid={{Convert|0.000981553|AU|km|abbr=on}} | jupiter_moid={{Convert|3.59473|AU|Gm|abbr=on}} }}
'''{{mp|2010 AL|30}}''' is a [[near-Earth asteroid]] that was discovered on 10 January 2010.<ref name=jpldata>{{cite web |title=JPL Small-Body Database Browser |url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=2010AL30;cad=1 |accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>
Italian scientists Ernesto Guido and Giovanni Sostero told [[RIA Novosti]] that it had an orbital period of almost exactly one year and might be a spent rocket booster.<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-01-14/us/28126845_1_object-orbit-amateur-telescope What was that Mystery object whizzes past Earth], The Times of India, January 14, 2010</ref> However, it was determined that it is a near-Earth asteroid.<ref>[http://neo.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news167.html Small Asteroid 2010 AL30 Will Fly Past The Earth]. [[NASA]]/[[JPL]] Near-Earth Object Program, January 12, 2010.</ref>
On January 13, 2010 at 1246 UT it passed Earth at {{convert|0.0008624|AU|km mi|abbr=on|lk=on}},<ref name=jpldata/> about 1/3 of the distance from the Earth to the Moon (or 0.33 [[Lunar distance (astronomy)|LD]]).
Based an estimated diameter of {{convert|10|-|15|m|ft|abbr=on}}, if 2010 AL30 had entered the Earth's atmosphere, it would have created an [[air burst]] equivalent to between 50 kT and 100 kT ([[TNT equivalent|kilotons of TNT]]). The Nagasaki "[[Fat Man]]" atom bomb had a yield between 13–18 kT.<ref>[http://epod.usra.edu/blog/2010/03/nearearth-object-2010-al30.html Near-Earth Object 2010 AL30]. [[NASA]] Earth Science Picture of the Day March 06, 2010.</ref>
It has an [[Uncertainty Parameter U|uncertainty parameter]] of 2 and has been observed by [[radar astronomy|radar]].<ref name=jpldata/> Radar observations show the asteroid is elongated and is about 30 meters in diameter.<ref name="echo"/> It may be a [[contact binary (small Solar System body)|contact binary]].
