{{Multiple issues| {{more citations needed|date=December 2013}} {{Advert|date=September 2014}} }}
{{Infobox Organization |name = Verified Carbon Standard |image = |image_border = |size = |caption = |map = |msize = |mcaption = |abbreviation = |motto = |formation = 2005 |extinction = |type = Nonprofit [[501(c)3]] |status = |purpose = A carbon accounting standard and organisation. |headquarters =Washington, D.C. |location = |region_served = |Offices = Santiago, Chile, Beijing China, San Paulo, Brazil |language = |leader_title = CEO |leader_name = [http://verra.org/staff/david-antonioli/ David Antonioli] |main_organ = |parent_organization = |affiliations = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = http://verra.org/ |remarks = }}
The [http://verra.org/project/vcs-program/ '''Verified Carbon Standard''' (VCS)], formerly the Voluntary Carbon Standard,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peters-Stanley |first1=Molly |title=Regulators Embrace Voluntary Carbon |url=https://www.forest-trends.org/ecosystem_marketplace/regulators-embrace-voluntary-carbon/ |accessdate=2018-09-17 |publisher=Ecosystem Marketplace |date=2011-03-15}}</ref> is a standard for certifying carbon emissions reductions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Verified Carbon Standard |url=http://verra.org/project/vcs-program/ |website=Verra |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref> VCS is administered by Verra, a 501(c)(3) not-for-profit organization.<ref>{{cite web |title=Who We Are |url=http://verra.org/about-verra/who-we-are/ |website=Verra |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref>
In 2005, [[The Climate Group]], [http://www.ieta.org International Emissions Trading Association (IETA)] and The [[World Economic Forum]] - convened a team of global carbon market experts to draft the first VCS requirements. The [[World Business Council for Sustainable Development]] (WBCSD) joined the effort soon after. These experts soon formed the VCS Steering Committee, which worked to draft the first and subsequent versions of the VCS Standard. Many of the members of the original steering committee went on to be on the original [http://verra.org/about-verra/board-of-directors/ Board of Directors], which now has evolved into a body of 12 members that offers input and guidance to the organization.
By 2008, with the VCS Standard becoming more widely adopted, the Board of Directors named [http://verra.org/staff/david-antonioli/ David Antonioli] the organization’s first Chief Executive Officer. Soon after in 2009, VCS incorporated in [[Washington D.C.]] as a non-profit NGO.
On February 15, 2018, the organization that maintains the Verified Carbon Standard changed its name from Verified Carbon Standard to Verra.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zwick |first1=Steve |title=Verified Carbon Standard Changes Name To Verra |url=https://www.forest-trends.org/ecosystem_marketplace/verified-carbon-standard-changes-name-verra/ |date=2018-02-15}}</ref>
